DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(92)90033-V
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669290033V
AB  - This study examines the efficiency performance of the minority-owned banks (MOBs) as multiproduct firms relative to that of the nonminority banks (NMOBs) using a highly flexible nonparametric approach. Since MOBs and NMOBs employ distinct technologies the efficiency indices for the two groups are derived relative to their respective group-specific frontiers and are contrasted to shed light on the ownership-efficiency relationship. The MOB sample is then disaggregated and the intra-group efficiency differentials are investigated. The findings support the hypothesis that abstracting the regional, regulatory, size, and maturity characteristics of banks, efficiency differentials between MOBs and NMOBs are statistically insignificant.
